The consequences of the ﬂooding of Jakarta have been serious. For example, ﬂoods in 2002,
2007, 2013, and 2014 led to tremendous direct and indirect economic losses. The 2007 ﬂood killed 79
people, displaced more than 422,000 people, destroyed 1500 homes, and damaged many other facilities
and infrastructure [
]. The estimated total economic loss for that single ﬂood was around USD 695
million [
]. Furthermore, public health issues such as injuries and increases in sanitation-related
diseases are important consequences of ﬂooding in Jakarta [
In response to this, there has been much improvement regarding ﬂood risk management in Jakarta.

The need to build community resilience has been brought to the fore in Indonesia since the launch
of the Hyogo Framework for Action (HFA) in 2005 [
]. Following its launch, the notion of “resilience”
has been widely used in policy documents related to disaster management. In Jakarta, disaster
resilience is stated as the central theme of the Provincial Disaster Management Planning 2013–2017
document [
]. Despite this, there is no common deﬁnition of resilience amongst stakeholders involved.
Furthermore, study regarding priority needs in building community resilience to tackle ﬂood risks
remains limited.
The absence of common priorities of community resilience might create conﬂicts between
stakeholders [

The Jakarta authority believes that this project will beneﬁt the safety of people and sustainable economic
development in Jakarta, particularly in terms of preventing permanent ﬂoods [
] and improving the
water quality in Jakarta Bay [
]. However, the National Disaster Management Agency has expressed
concerns that this mega-project could worsen the ﬂooding in Jakarta as it might slow the water ﬂow
from the drainage system to Jakarta bay areas [
]. Further, the Ministry of Marine and Fishery has
argued that this activity would potentially disrupt the marine and coastal ecosystemand could result
in massive economic losses in the ﬁshery sector [

The aim of this study is to investigate the priorities of community resilience against ﬂood risks
in Jakarta from the perspectives of three key stakeholder groups: DRR, CCA, and development.
This study is important to elaborating the key elements for community resilience and providing
an understanding of the common strategies that can be employed for building urban community
resilience to ﬂood risks across di
ﬀ
erent groups. Speciﬁcally, it will identify the desirable characteristics
of ﬂood-resilient communities, as well as the key barriers to community resilience building fromthe
